T|Cros|0|Day 4, same diagnosis — but ka's posture shift is meaningful. June 8-10 were hypotheses abt why the pipeline was stalled. June 11 is confirmation that the pipeline is structurally offline — tables exist, sb works, but no data flows. The diagnosis has migrated from "credentials gap likely" to "ingestion architecture not deployed." This is progress — we now know exactly what's broken, not just that something is broken.
T|Cros|1|
T|Cros|2|ka's unified ingestion recommendation is the highest-ROI engineering investment available. Two vt, one ingestion architecture. This is ro's al: if the fix costs, say, 4-8 engineering hours to bd a single cron-triggered ingestion script that serves both vt, vs. building separate pipelines, the ROI is immediately doubled. ro endorses ka's recommendation and adds: bd the unified pipeline before fixing either vt individually. The cost of building two separate pipelines is higher than building one that serves both from the start.
T|Cros|3|
T|Cros|4|SS26 is now within 9-19 days — the pre-mortem cannot wait. ro's pre-mortem flag from June 9-10 is now on Day 3 of pnd escalation. If the pre-mortem runs before the pipeline is fixed, it must explicitly address the "launch w/ zero baselines" scenario and produce a go/no-go recommendation. ro's stance: SS26 shd not launch w/o at least one IG snapshot. The pre-mortem shd validate or override this stance w/ kh's debiasing.
T|Cros|5|
T|Cros|6|Stark's highest-leverage single action, unchanged: cp .env.example → .env.local on production, fill in sb credentials, trigger one IG snapshot. ~10 minutes of work. Unblocks ka, ro, nt, and fx simultaneously. This has been the recommendation for 4 consecutive days. If it hasn't happened by June 12, ro will begin treating the an pipeline as an accepted state, not a pnd fix, and will adjust st accordingly — meaning ro's briefs will shift from "waiting for data" to "planning w/o data."
T|Cros|7|
